Mischievous Responders

Author

Seungju Kim

1 Criteria

To identify and remove problematic responders, we will employ a rubric to classify all respondents into Extremely High, High, Moderate, and Low risk of problematic responses.

The rubric is as follows:

Tier 4: Removal Tier 3: High Risk Tier 2: Moderate Risk Tier 1: Low Risk
1 EH 2+ Highs 1 High + 1-2 Meds All else
1 High + 3 Meds 3 Meds + 1 Low
4 Meds

Three datasets will be created from these classifications: SGIP3_data.sav, SGIP2_data.sav, SGIP1_data. Any responses categorized as Extremely High will be removed from all responses.

We will be using the following four criterias for the rubric: Time to complete, Longstring value, IRV value, Attention, and Text response when applicable.

2 Preparation

Load relevant libraries.

Load the data

Show the code 
org_data <- read_sav("SGI_raw_data.sav")
data <- org_data

3 Time

We will utilize the Star and End times of respondents to determine duration to complete the data. We will employ the following rubric:

Classification Duration
Extremely High <15 Minutes
High <30 Minutes
Moderate <45 Minutes
Low >45 Minutes

Before starting we will calcuate the duration to complete by calculating the difference between Start and End time.

Show the code 
# Reformat the data
data$StartDate <- as.POSIXct(data$StartDate, format = "%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p")
data$EndDate <- as.POSIXct(data$EndDate, format = "%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p")
# Find the difference in Minutes.
data$Duration <- as.numeric(difftime(data$EndDate, data$StartDate, units = "mins"))

Next, we will examine a boxplot and the distribution of time to complete.

Show the code 
# Boxplot of the minutes
boxplot(data$Duration)
Note

We should note first of course that boxplots will not be helpful, as the extreme outliers will distort our view of the average response.

Show the code 
# Distribution of Duration to complete
p <- ggplot(data, aes(x = Duration)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, color = "black", fill = "blue") +
  labs(title = "Interactive Histogram of Duration")
ggplotly(p)
Warning: Removed 1 rows containing non-finite values (`stat_bin()`).
Note

What we see here is that the outliers make it difficult to still see the responses we are really worried about: straightliners and mischievous responders. Let’s narrow the graph to show those under 2 hours.

Show the code 
# Distribution of Duration to complete
p <- data %>%
  filter(Duration <120) %>%
  ggplot( aes(x = Duration)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Interactive Histogram of Duration <2 Hours")
ggplotly(p)
Note

We see more informative distribution of duration. It looks like we have several responses that are indeed completed before 30 minutes. Let’s take a closer look.

Show the code 
# Distribution of Duration to complete
p <- data %>%
  filter(Duration <60) %>%
  ggplot( aes(x = Duration)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Interactive Histogram of Duration 1 Hour")
ggplotly(p)
Tip

If you hover your mouse over the bars, you can see the count of each response.

Let’s examine the number of respondents in Extremely High, High, Moderate, and Low risk based on their Duration.

3.1 Results

Show the code 
# Assign Classification
data <- data %>%
  mutate(DurClass = case_when(
    Duration <= 15 ~ "Extremely High Risk",
    Duration >= 16 & Duration <= 30 ~ "High Risk",
    Duration >= 31 & Duration <= 45 ~ "Moderate Risk",
    Duration > 45 ~ "Low Risk",
    TRUE ~ NA_character_  # For cases that don't fit any criteria
  ))
Show the code 
nice_table(table(data$DurClass))

Var1

Freq

Extremely High Risk

742

High Risk

397

Low Risk

656

Moderate Risk

382

Warning

Our findings show that 742 respondents completed the survey under 15 minutes. These responders will be automatically removed from the dataset, and will not be retained.

3.2 Removal

Show the code 
data <- data %>%
  filter(DurClass != "Extremely High Risk")
nice_table(table(data$DurClass))

Var1

Freq

High Risk

397

Low Risk

656

Moderate Risk

382

We can confirm that now Extremely High Risk were removed from the data. We have a total of 1435 respondents retained as of now.

4 Longstring

Let us examined those who straight-lined. We will utilize the following rubric for classification:

Classification Longstring Value
Extremely High >40
High 23-39
Moderate 14-23
Low <14

data$long <- longstring(data)

boxplot(data$long, main = "Boxplot of Longstring")

Warning

Contrary to the subset dataset, we see that several respondents scored grater than 40! For this reason I have added a Extremely High classification such that if Longstring value is >40 then they will be automatically removed.

Show the code 
# Assign Classification
data <- data %>%
  mutate(LongClass = case_when(
    long >= 40 ~ "Extremely High Risk",
    long >= 24 & long <= 39 ~ "High Risk",
    long >= 14 & long <= 23 ~ "Moderate Risk",
    long < 14 ~ "Low Risk",
    TRUE ~ NA_character_  # For cases that don't fit any criteria
  ))

5 IRV

Now we will examine straight-lining across Scales in the beginning, middle, and end of the survey. The classification rubric is as follows:

Classification IRV Value
High Straight-lined on 3 measures
Moderate Straight-lined on 1-2 measures
Low Straight-lined on no measures

The table shows that there are 21 individuals whom straight-lined on this measure and two who scored above the 75th quartile. Let’s apply the criteria.

Show the code 
# Calculating quartiles
lower_quartile <- quantile(data$irv_saq, probs = 0.25, na.rm = TRUE)
upper_quartile <- quantile(data$irv_saq, probs = 0.75, na.rm = TRUE)
high_quartile <- quantile(data$irv_saq, probs = 0.90, na.rm = TRUE)

# Adding a classification based on quartiles
data <- data %>%
  mutate(irv_saq_class = case_when(
    irv_saq == 0 ~ "Straight-lining",
    irv_saq <= lower_quartile ~ "Reasonable",
    irv_saq > lower_quartile & irv_saq < high_quartile ~ "Reasonable",
    irv_saq >= high_quartile ~ "Random Response",
    TRUE ~ NA_character_  # For cases that don't fit any criteria
  ))

data <- data %>%

8 Final Criteria Application

Note

Extremely High Risk will not be displayed as they were removed.

We will be using the four variables: DurClass, LongClass, IRVClass, AttClass and apply our rubric.

Show the code 
data <- data %>%
  mutate(
    HighRiskCount = (DurClass == "High Risk") + (LongClass == "High Risk") + (IRVClass == "High Risk") + (AttClass == "High Risk"),
    ModerateRiskCount = (DurClass == "Moderate Risk") + (LongClass == "Moderate Risk") + (IRVClass == "Moderate Risk") + (AttClass == "Moderate Risk"),
    LowRiskCount = (DurClass == "Low Risk") + (LongClass == "Low Risk") + (IRVClass == "Low Risk") + (AttClass == "Low Risk")
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    Tier = case_when(
      HighRiskCount >= 2 ~ "Tier 3: High Risk",
      HighRiskCount == 1 & ModerateRiskCount == 3 ~ "Tier 3: High Risk",
      ModerateRiskCount == 4 ~ "Tier 3: High Risk",
      HighRiskCount == 1 & ModerateRiskCount >= 1 & LowRiskCount >= 1 ~ "Tier 2: Moderate Risk",
      ModerateRiskCount == 3 & LowRiskCount == 1 ~ "Tier 2: Moderate Risk",
      TRUE ~ "Tier 1: Low Risk"
    )
  ) %>%
  select(-HighRiskCount, -ModerateRiskCount, -LowRiskCount) # Optional: Remove the count columns if not needed
